    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-11-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-11-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="245"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d245">
                <head>245. Letter From the Special Representative for Trade Negotiations (<persName
                        corresp="#p_HCAJ1" type="from">Herter</persName>) to the Director of the
                    Bureau of the Budget (<persName corresp="#p_GK3" type="to"
                        >Gordon</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d245fn1">Source:
                        Washington National Records Center, RG 40, Secretary of Commerce Files: FRC
                        69 <gloss target="#t_A1">A</gloss> 6828, Textiles, President’s Advisory
                        Committee. No classification marking.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-11-30">November 30, 1964</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Dear Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GK3">Gordon</persName>:</p>
                <p>I am enclosing for appropriate action an amendment to Executive Order No. 11052,
                    entitled “Cotton Textiles and Cotton Textile Products”.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d245fn2">Not printed. The amendment to Executive Order 11052 was
                        issued on April 7, 1965, as Executive Order 11214. For text, see Federal
                        Register, April 8, 1965, p. 4527.</note>
                </p>
                <p>As a result of this amendment, this Office would be represented on both the
                    President’s Cabinet Textile Advisory Committee and the Interagency Textile
                    Administrative Committee. In addition, a representative of this Office would
                    serve on the United States Delegation to the Cotton Textiles Committee of the
                    General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.</p>
                <p>I believe that the proposed amendment is appropriate for the following reasons.
                    First, it is clear that international trade in cotton and other textiles will
                    have a considerable bearing upon the conduct of the Kennedy Round in Geneva.
                    Second, Executive Order No. 11075, as amended, establishing this Office provides
                    that the Special Representative for Trade Negotiations shall advise the
                    President with respect to international commodity agreements, such as the
                    Long-Term Arrangement on cotton textiles.</p>
                <p>I would appreciate whatever can be done to expedite consideration of this
                    proposed executive order.</p>
                <p>Most sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HCAJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Christian A. Herter</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="3" xml:id="d245fn3">Printed from a copy that indicates <persName
                                corresp="#p_HCAJ1">Herter</persName> signed the original.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
